  "local_port": 49624,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some cultural faux pas in Hungary?",
  "response": "When visiting Hungary or interacting with Hungarian culture, being aware of local customs and social norms can help you navigate social situations smoothly and avoid unintended offenses. Here are some common cultural faux pas to be mindful of:\n\n1. **Improper Greetings:**\n   - **Handshake Formality:** In Hungary, a firm handshake while maintaining eye contact is a common and respectful greeting, especially in formal settings. Using a too-lax handshake or avoiding eye contact can be perceived as disinterest.\n   - **Use of Titles:** Addressing someone by their first name immediately, especially in formal or professional contexts, can be considered disrespectful. It's polite to use titles like \"Mr.\" (\u00dar) or \"Mrs./Ms.\" (Asszony) followed by their surname until invited to use their first name.\n\n2. **Disrespecting Personal Space:**\n   - Hungarians value personal space, especially in public places. Standing too close or being overly touchy can make others uncomfortable.\n\n3. **Casual Attitude in Formal Settings:**\n   - Taking a too-casual approach in formal situations, such as business meetings or official events, may be seen as disrespectful. Dressing appropriately and adhering to formal protocols is appreciated.\n\n4. **Inappropriate Table Manners:**\n   - **Proper Use of Utensils:** Unlike some cultures where hands can be used while eating certain foods, Hungarian etiquette typically requires the use of utensils for most dishes.\n   - **Stay Seated Until Everyone Is Served:** Leaving the table before everyone has been served or finishing your meal before others can be considered rude.\n\n5. **Neglecting to Open Gifts in Front of the Giver:**\n   - When presented with a gift, it is customary to open it in the giver's presence. Failing to do so might seem ungrateful or insincere.\n\n6. **Disregarding Language Politeness:**\n   - Using informal language or slang with strangers or in formal situations can be seen as disrespectful. Even if you\u2019re not fluent in Hungarian, attempting polite phrases and showing effort can be appreciated.\n\n7. **Discussing Sensitive Historical or Political Topics:**\n   - Topics such as Hungary\u2019s history during World War II, the Soviet era, and current political issues can be sensitive. Approach these subjects with caution and respect, avoiding heated debates unless you are well-informed and sure of the context.\n\n8. **Public Displays of Affection in Certain Contexts:**\n   - While moderate public displays of affection are generally acceptable, excessive displays, especially in religious or very traditional settings, might be frowned upon.\n\n9. **Smoking Etiquette:**\n   - Smoking is banned in many public places in Hungary, including restaurants, bars, and public transport. Always look for designated smoking areas to avoid fines and respect non-smokers.\n\n10. **Ignoring Tipping Customs:**\n    - Tipping is customary in Hungary, typically around 10-15% in restaurants. Not leaving a tip where it is expected can be considered impolite.\n\n11. **Punctuality:**\n    - Being late, especially for business appointments or formal events, is seen as disrespectful. Aim to arrive on time or a few minutes early.\n\n12. **Handling Money Properly:**\n    - When exchanging money, always count it discreetly and ensure you receive the correct change. Mishandling financial transactions can lead to misunderstandings or unintentional disrespect.\n\n**Tips to Avoid Cultural Faux Pas:**\n\n- **Learn Basic Hungarian Phrases:** Even a few words like \"please\" (k\u00e9rem), \"thank you\" (k\u00f6sz\u00f6n\u00f6m), and \"hello\" (szia) can go a long way in showing respect.\n- **Observe and Adapt:** Pay attention to how locals behave in different settings and try to emulate respectful practices.\n- **Ask When Unsure:** If you're uncertain about proper etiquette, it's perfectly acceptable to politely ask for guidance.\n\nRespecting local customs not only helps in avoiding faux pas but also enriches your cultural experience in Hungary. Being considerate and observant will be appreciated by Hungarians and can lead to more meaningful interactions.",
  "response_tokens": [
